1
00:01:40,111 --> 00:01:41,450
Is Mr Sherwood Nash in?

2
00:01:41,550 --> 00:01:42,861
Have you an appointment?

3
00:01:42,961 --> 00:01:45,563
Well, not exactly. But could he see me?

4
00:01:46,877 --> 00:01:47,891
Go right in.

5
00:01:48,407 --> 00:01:51,100
Yes. But you see Mr Curtis,
it was a very small issue.

6
00:01:51,875 --> 00:01:54,481
Yes, only five million dollars and
we sold practically all of it.

7
00:01:54,981 --> 00:01:58,231
I guess we can allot you 10,000 shares.

8
00:01:58,746 --> 00:02:01,653
Would you hold the wire a moment. Sit
down. I'll be with you in just a second.

9
00:02:01,966 --> 00:02:02,752
Thank you.

10
00:02:03,054 --> 00:02:04,329
Hello, Mr Spencer?

11
00:02:05,268 --> 00:02:07,522
Hey. That stock had a rise of
five and a half points today.

12
00:02:07,735 --> 00:02:09,283
Sell 5,000 at the market?

13
00:02:09,474 --> 00:02:11,116
Alright I'll take care of that for you.

14
00:02:11,216 --> 00:02:11,945
Goodbye.

15
00:02:13,607 --> 00:02:14,345
Cigar?

16
00:02:17,494 --> 00:02:19,232
Thank you.
- Hello, Mr Curtis.

17
00:02:21,343 --> 00:02:23,417
Well, in my opinion that would
be very good judgement.

18
00:02:24,511 --> 00:02:26,674
Alright. You'll take 10,000 shares?

19
00:02:28,259 --> 00:02:30,018
Yes. I'll hold the wire.

20
00:02:31,299 --> 00:02:32,086
Well, sir?

21
00:02:33,136 --> 00:02:34,299
What can I do for you?

22
00:02:34,921 --> 00:02:36,588
I've come to take the telephones out.

23
00:02:36,845 --> 00:02:38,927
They've been disconnected
for three days.

24
00:02:51,417 --> 00:02:52,517
Good day, folks.

25
00:02:55,978 --> 00:02:58,240
What's he doing with the phones?
- Taking them for a walk.

26
00:02:58,742 --> 00:02:59,567
Any luck?

27
00:03:00,604 --> 00:03:02,393
Couldn't you raise anything?
- Not a dime.

28
00:03:02,665 --> 00:03:04,579
Well, mastermind. Now what?

29
00:03:05,180 --> 00:03:06,796
Don't rush me. I'll think of something.

30
00:03:06,954 --> 00:03:08,668
I'd hate to hold my breath until you do.

31
00:03:09,245 --> 00:03:10,359
[ Door knocks ]

32
00:03:10,874 --> 00:03:11,603
Come in.

33
00:03:15,111 --> 00:03:17,050
Well sir, what can do for you?

34
00:03:17,402 --> 00:03:18,981
We've come to move out the furniture.

35
00:03:21,509 --> 00:03:23,472
It's all yours.
- That's right.

36
00:03:26,562 --> 00:03:27,749
What's the idea, Glenda?

37
00:03:27,849 --> 00:03:30,265
Something tells me the Golden
Harvest Investment Corporation ..

38
00:03:30,365 --> 00:03:31,972
Is about ready to rest in peace.

39
00:03:32,523 --> 00:03:33,882
I'm not much fun at a funeral.

40
00:03:34,311 --> 00:03:35,416
So, toot-toot.

41
00:03:36,454 --> 00:03:38,085
A lovely girl when you're in the money.

42
00:03:39,011 --> 00:03:40,398
Don't worry. She'll be back.

43
00:03:41,241 --> 00:03:42,628
Where do we go from here, boss?

44
00:03:43,302 --> 00:03:43,974
Shush.

45
00:03:44,563 --> 00:03:45,450
I'm thinking.

46
00:03:46,805 --> 00:03:47,420
Hey.

47
00:03:47,850 --> 00:03:49,252
Oh .. sorry.

48
00:03:50,195 --> 00:03:52,148
We got find ourselves a new racket.

49
00:03:54,090 --> 00:03:55,785
Could we promote a dance marathon maybe?

50
00:03:56,677 --> 00:03:58,282
Dancing lessons by mail.

51
00:03:59,223 --> 00:04:00,445
How about a bunion derby.

52
00:04:01,204 --> 00:04:02,420
A bathing beauty contest.

53
00:04:02,906 --> 00:04:05,025
A pretty baby parade. A snail race.

54
00:04:06,267 --> 00:04:08,438
Boss, I got the idea.
- Look, Snap.

55
00:04:09,058 --> 00:04:11,106
Would you do me a favor?
- Certainly. Anything, boss.

56
00:04:11,206 --> 00:04:13,440
Just let me alone for a minute.
I'll think of something.

57
00:04:13,540 --> 00:04:14,444
Sure you will.

58
00:04:19,927 --> 00:04:21,096
Excuse me, boss.

59
00:04:21,579 --> 00:04:23,071
Oh, nothing matters.

60
00:04:37,585 --> 00:04:38,705
It's alright.

61
00:04:38,926 --> 00:04:41,269
Yes, sir. It's alright.

62
00:04:42,298 --> 00:04:43,057
Snap?

63
00:04:43,683 --> 00:04:44,756
Just a minute, boss.

64
00:04:45,415 --> 00:04:46,725
Mr Nash - Miss Mason.

65
00:04:47,652 --> 00:04:49,411
How do you do.
- How do you do, Miss Mason.

66
00:04:49,645 --> 00:04:50,682
Oh, call her Lynn.

67
00:04:51,831 --> 00:04:52,641
Shall I?

68
00:04:53,126 --> 00:04:53,899
Why not?

69
00:04:54,573 --> 00:04:55,717
Isn't that cute?

70
00:04:56,966 --> 00:04:57,753
Very cute.

71
00:04:58,256 --> 00:04:59,933
Oh, get a load of this one.

72
00:05:02,187 --> 00:05:02,880
Say.

73
00:05:03,195 --> 00:05:04,958
Well, is that your work?

74
00:05:05,192 --> 00:05:05,836
Sure.

75
00:05:05,966 --> 00:05:08,251
So what do you do with them?
- Sell them if I can.

76
00:05:12,164 --> 00:05:13,036
They're sold.

77
00:05:13,842 --> 00:05:14,829
What do you mean?

78
00:05:17,105 --> 00:05:17,834
An idea.

79
00:05:51,207 --> 00:05:52,434
This is rather stunning.

80
00:05:53,151 --> 00:05:54,081
How much is it?

81
00:05:54,293 --> 00:05:55,555
$375.

82
00:05:56,193 --> 00:05:57,339
A bit dear, Mr Duryea.

83
00:05:57,715 --> 00:05:58,902
Isn't that rather steep?

84
00:05:59,410 --> 00:06:01,101
Not for an exclusive Parisian model.

85
00:06:01,952 --> 00:06:03,248
Is it really exclusive?

86
00:06:03,459 --> 00:06:04,660
My dear Mrs Van Tyle.

87
00:06:04,923 --> 00:06:06,519
It arrived from Paris six days ago.

88
00:06:06,886 --> 00:06:08,703
There isn't another one
like it in the world.

89
00:06:09,379 --> 00:06:10,887
In that case, I'll take it.

90
00:06:11,929 --> 00:06:13,838
The very latest thing from Paris, Mary.

91
00:06:14,119 --> 00:06:15,878
How do you like it?
- Very becoming, Madam.

92
00:06:16,342 --> 00:06:17,272
[ Door knocks ]

93
00:06:17,405 --> 00:06:18,205
Come in.

94
00:06:19,222 --> 00:06:21,725
I beg your pardon, Madam. The young
woman from the employment agency.

95
00:06:21,846 --> 00:06:23,092
I'll see her right away.

96
00:06:25,302 --> 00:06:26,626
Good afternoon.

97
00:06:27,167 --> 00:06:30,454
They sent me over from the Acme Agency.

98
00:06:30,957 --> 00:06:32,376
Where did you get that dress?

99
00:06:32,869 --> 00:06:34,399
Well, can you beat that?

100
00:06:34,825 --> 00:06:36,424
You got a suit like mine.

101
00:06:37,115 --> 00:06:39,021
I got it over at Rosenthal's basement.

102
00:06:39,357 --> 00:06:41,044
Sixteen ninety-five.

103
00:06:41,209 --> 00:06:42,531
Sixteen ninety-five?

104
00:06:44,656 --> 00:06:46,618
Kind of a gyp at that, but ..

105
00:06:46,942 --> 00:06:49,539
I like to be well dressed.
- Oh, go away.

106
00:06:50,407 --> 00:06:51,472
Give me Mr Duryea.

107
00:06:53,279 --> 00:06:55,332
Yes .. yes, I quite agree with you.

108
00:06:56,376 --> 00:06:57,363
It is an outrage.

109
00:06:58,416 --> 00:06:59,099
Yes.

110
00:06:59,820 --> 00:07:00,916
Yes, of course.

111
00:07:04,049 --> 00:07:05,894
The seventh time that's
happened in two weeks.

112
00:07:06,654 --> 00:07:07,555
Take a letter.

113
00:07:07,713 --> 00:07:10,495
Send copies to Caponelli,
Glass and Feldman.

114
00:07:12,739 --> 00:07:17,117
It is imperative that we organise
to stamp out the copying evil.

115
00:07:18,398 --> 00:07:19,954
Which is undermining our business.

116
00:07:21,633 --> 00:07:24,875
Therefore it is necessary that
we get together immediately.

117
00:07:38,530 --> 00:07:39,374
Hi Jules.

118
00:07:40,523 --> 00:07:41,338
Read this.

119
00:07:42,776 --> 00:07:43,362
Ha.

120
00:07:44,225 --> 00:07:45,506
Pirates, huh?
- Yes.

121
00:07:45,832 --> 00:07:47,736
That's why I'm here. I don't like it.

122
00:07:48,194 --> 00:07:49,581
I don't want to get in any jam.

123
00:07:50,129 --> 00:07:51,431
What are you worrying about?

124
00:07:52,333 --> 00:07:56,029
All you're doing is buying photographs
and sketches of dresses from me.

125
00:07:56,363 --> 00:07:57,779
You don't know where I get them.

126
00:07:58,015 --> 00:08:01,066
I'm the bootlegger. You're just the
customer. Nothing can happen to you.

127
00:08:01,261 --> 00:08:02,921
I hope you're right.
- Of course I am.

128
00:08:03,387 --> 00:08:04,727
What about today's models?

129
00:08:04,962 --> 00:08:06,357
I'm expecting them any minute.

130
00:08:06,457 --> 00:08:08,216
The Isle De France
docked only an hour ago.

131
00:08:12,385 --> 00:08:14,137
I told you that but you'll never learn.

132
00:08:14,341 --> 00:08:15,639
You will never learn.

133
00:08:18,008 --> 00:08:19,281
Hi, Chief.
- Good evening.

134
00:08:19,381 --> 00:08:20,568
Did the boat get in yet?

135
00:08:21,063 --> 00:08:23,695
Sure. Harry will be here any minute.
- Well, we're all set for it.

136
00:08:24,571 --> 00:08:25,626
Winnings?
- No.

137
00:08:25,870 --> 00:08:27,819
Unlucky at cards, lucky in love.

138
00:08:31,194 --> 00:08:32,868
How are they coming?
- Alright, I think.

139
00:08:33,034 --> 00:08:34,536
Would you like to see them?
- Yes.

140
00:08:35,543 --> 00:08:36,787
Kinda like her, don't you?

141
00:08:37,653 --> 00:08:39,162
I always admire efficiency.

142
00:08:39,377 --> 00:08:41,377
Efficiency? I never heard
it called that before.

143
00:08:42,292 --> 00:08:44,405
Say, what's the matter?
Isn't she running this alright?

144
00:08:44,505 --> 00:08:46,198
She's running you alright but not me.

145
00:08:50,436 --> 00:08:51,537
I'll attend to this.

146
00:08:51,637 --> 00:08:54,101
Hey, wait a minute. Who found her?

147
00:08:54,341 --> 00:08:56,913
I did. You never even met her until ..
- Young man ..

148
00:08:57,337 --> 00:08:58,982
You are stopping the wheels of industry.

149
00:08:59,570 --> 00:09:00,574
Alright.

150
00:09:01,200 --> 00:09:02,340
Snap.
- Alright.

151
00:09:04,579 --> 00:09:06,158
Well how is my first Lieutenant?

152
00:09:06,758 --> 00:09:07,917
No complaints, Captain.

153
00:09:08,103 --> 00:09:09,618
Here is Harry. Let's get going.

154
00:09:36,011 --> 00:09:37,084
Come on. Step on it.

155
00:09:40,424 --> 00:09:41,963
Hello Harry.
- Hello, Glenda.

156
00:09:44,081 --> 00:09:45,441
No time for oohs and aahs.

157
00:09:45,970 --> 00:09:47,300
Let's get the hooks and eyes.

158
00:09:50,892 --> 00:09:51,564
Right.

159
00:09:54,511 --> 00:09:55,469
Camera is ready.

160
00:09:58,277 --> 00:09:59,350
Which girl is first?

161
00:10:00,245 --> 00:10:01,647
Ouch.
- What's the trouble?

162
00:10:03,304 --> 00:10:05,085
I don't know. I think
it caught somewhere.

163
00:10:05,896 --> 00:10:07,083
Can I help?
- Hurry up.

164
00:10:07,303 --> 00:10:08,147
Alright now.

165
00:10:09,226 --> 00:10:10,234
Where is it?

166
00:10:12,650 --> 00:10:15,155
What are you playing? Blind man's bluff?

167
00:10:15,875 --> 00:10:16,834
There it is.

168
00:10:17,522 --> 00:10:18,436
Just a moment.

169
00:10:19,820 --> 00:10:21,365
Next girl please. Hurry.

170
00:10:22,323 --> 00:10:24,356
Say, isn't that a beauty?
- Isn't it.

171
00:10:24,879 --> 00:10:26,610
But I think it needs
the other background.

172
00:10:27,029 --> 00:10:28,359
Let's get this one. It's hot.

173
00:10:28,459 --> 00:10:29,972
Hey, what's the big idea?

174
00:10:31,455 --> 00:10:32,897
Well.
- Oh, my mistake.

175
00:10:33,670 --> 00:10:34,767
Isn't that a honey?

176
00:10:35,918 --> 00:10:36,619
Got it.

177
00:10:36,933 --> 00:10:39,118
Come on children, step on it.
Before the fashion changes.

178
00:10:41,569 --> 00:10:42,801
Here is the last one.

179
00:10:42,973 --> 00:10:46,144
Look at them. I'm getting
better and better every day.

180
00:10:46,588 --> 00:10:47,962
Here is the material for it.

181
00:10:49,537 --> 00:10:50,405
Pretty, huh?

182
00:10:50,748 --> 00:10:51,363
Hey.

183
00:10:51,928 --> 00:10:53,122
Oh, sorry.

184
00:10:54,476 --> 00:10:55,518
Crook.
- Robber.

185
00:10:55,790 --> 00:10:57,255
Cheat. Who paid you for this?

186
00:10:57,448 --> 00:10:59,438
You'd better tell.
- Or the police will arrest you.

187
00:10:59,635 --> 00:11:02,043
Gentlemen, gentlemen.
We'll never get anywhere this way.

188
00:11:02,360 --> 00:11:03,907
Say, who are these guys anyway?

189
00:11:04,305 --> 00:11:06,017
These gentlemen are my competitors.

190
00:11:06,219 --> 00:11:08,015
Their drivers have been
betraying them too.

191
00:11:08,115 --> 00:11:10,888
Don't make me laugh. You guys got
nothing on me. Nothing has been stolen.

192
00:11:11,158 --> 00:11:12,259
I've had you watched.

193
00:11:12,529 --> 00:11:15,248
Every time we send you down to the pier
to pick up a shipment of new models.

194
00:11:15,557 --> 00:11:17,940
You parked in an alley so these
crooks could take pictures.

195
00:11:18,338 --> 00:11:19,795
Before the models ever got to us.

196
00:11:19,895 --> 00:11:20,864
You're fired.

197
00:11:21,164 --> 00:11:23,059
Well, so long boys.
- Get out.

198
00:11:29,041 --> 00:11:29,818
Hello?

199
00:11:30,714 --> 00:11:31,983
Oh Harry, what is it?

200
00:11:32,215 --> 00:11:33,345
I've just been canned.

201
00:11:34,869 --> 00:11:35,513
Yeah.

202
00:11:36,164 --> 00:11:37,695
And tell the boss I'm all washed up.

203
00:11:41,172 --> 00:11:41,838
Well.

204
00:11:43,031 --> 00:11:43,818
Well what?

205
00:11:44,616 --> 00:11:45,288
Harry.

206
00:11:45,934 --> 00:11:47,047
He's fired.

207
00:11:48,663 --> 00:11:49,324
What?

208
00:11:49,587 --> 00:11:51,089
They've caught up with your racket.

209
00:11:51,913 --> 00:11:53,618
Mister mastermind.

210
00:11:56,382 --> 00:11:58,703
Well .. I'm not much fun with policemen.

211
00:11:59,126 --> 00:12:00,633
So I'm off to Buffalo.

212
00:12:01,059 --> 00:12:01,880
Toot-toot.

213
00:12:04,433 --> 00:12:06,348
Well, hadn't you better 'toot-toot' too?

214
00:12:06,772 --> 00:12:07,415
Nope.

215
00:12:08,093 --> 00:12:10,018
You should you know.
- Probably.

216
00:12:10,784 --> 00:12:11,943
I could get in trouble.

217
00:12:12,205 --> 00:12:13,429
I'll risk it, Captain.

218
00:12:21,700 --> 00:12:22,286
Oh.

219
00:12:23,717 --> 00:12:24,790
What is it, a ghost?

220
00:12:27,022 --> 00:12:27,751
An idea.

221
00:12:30,348 --> 00:12:31,592
Good afternoon, gentlemen.

222
00:12:31,913 --> 00:12:33,400
Mr Duryea.
- Yes?

223
00:12:34,128 --> 00:12:36,348
I understand you represent
the driver we just discharged.

224
00:12:37,933 --> 00:12:40,367
If you don't mind, I don't
believe I've had the pleasure.

225
00:12:41,052 --> 00:12:43,051
Mr Caponelli, Mr Glass, Mr Feldman.

226
00:12:43,438 --> 00:12:44,206
Charmed.

227
00:12:44,306 --> 00:12:45,003
Now.

228
00:12:45,185 --> 00:12:46,958
You are the attorney
for our driver, Brent?

229
00:12:47,058 --> 00:12:48,175
Well ..

230
00:12:48,387 --> 00:12:49,231
Not exactly.

231
00:12:50,019 --> 00:12:51,178
Well then, who are you?

232
00:12:51,514 --> 00:12:53,142
My name is Sherwood Nash.

233
00:12:53,335 --> 00:12:54,951
And what is your connection with Brent?

234
00:12:55,498 --> 00:12:57,730
He was fired for selling us out.
For taking a bribe.

235
00:12:58,017 --> 00:12:59,454
Oh, I'm the man who bribed him.

236
00:12:59,641 --> 00:13:00,944
You cheap crook.
- Thief.

237
00:13:01,170 --> 00:13:01,967
Robber.

238
00:13:02,067 --> 00:13:03,315
Of all the crooks.

239
00:13:03,759 --> 00:13:05,876
You are a pirate and a parasite
on legitimate business.

240
00:13:06,370 --> 00:13:09,241
We spend thousands and thousands of
dollars to import Paris models yet ..

241
00:13:09,435 --> 00:13:11,191
Ah, now you come to my point.

242
00:13:12,252 --> 00:13:15,491
Gentlemen, why spend those
thousands and thousands of dollars ..

243
00:13:15,967 --> 00:13:19,106
When you can have the identical models
delivered to you direct from Paris ..

244
00:13:19,433 --> 00:13:21,504
At a mere fraction
of their present cost.

245
00:13:23,525 --> 00:13:24,916
Nash, what are you driving at?

246
00:13:25,016 --> 00:13:26,517
I am merely trying to point out ..

247
00:13:26,617 --> 00:13:29,583
That I could just as easily be
working for you as against you.

248
00:13:30,562 --> 00:13:33,482
Instead of being the fly in
your coffee, so to speak.

249
00:13:33,762 --> 00:13:36,062
I could be the cream.
That, gentlemen, is why I'm here.

250
00:13:37,001 --> 00:13:40,322
I thought if we had a heart-to-heart
talk we might arrive at some ..

251
00:13:40,615 --> 00:13:41,819
Pleasant understanding.

252
00:13:42,600 --> 00:13:45,493
It occurred to me that a
man of my proven ability.

253
00:13:45,949 --> 00:13:47,336
Could be very valuable to you.

254
00:13:48,052 --> 00:13:48,810
In Paris.

255
00:13:50,349 --> 00:13:51,777
Do I make myself clear?

256
00:13:52,016 --> 00:13:53,833
Yes, I think you're a petty,
larcenous crook.

257
00:13:54,134 --> 00:13:56,002
You belong behind bars
and I'll put you there.

258
00:13:56,102 --> 00:13:57,681
Right. That's it.
- Twenty years.

259
00:13:57,862 --> 00:13:59,720
Now get out and find
yourself a good lawyer.

260
00:14:00,078 --> 00:14:01,036
You'll need one.

261
00:14:02,293 --> 00:14:03,079
Very well.

262
00:14:04,159 --> 00:14:06,938
If by any chance you wish
to get in touch with me ..

263
00:14:07,419 --> 00:14:09,226
I'm at the Park Manor hotel.

264
00:14:10,079 --> 00:14:10,866
Gentlemen.

265
00:14:13,429 --> 00:14:14,981
That's what I call 'nerve'.

266
00:14:15,262 --> 00:14:16,610
And a leech on the business.

267
00:14:16,915 --> 00:14:18,375
We've got to protect ourselves.

268
00:14:24,832 --> 00:14:26,068
Good evening.
- Mail?

269
00:14:26,837 --> 00:14:29,176
Three telephone calls for you, Mr Nash.
- Thank you.

270
00:14:36,476 --> 00:14:39,616
You mustn't get the idea that I'm asking
you to steal models for me in Paris.

271
00:14:40,223 --> 00:14:43,885
What I want is an idea of
the general style trends.

272
00:14:44,172 --> 00:14:45,463
The materials favored.

273
00:14:46,196 --> 00:14:48,820
The new lines and ..
- Possibly a few sketches?

274
00:14:49,097 --> 00:14:51,738
Well yes. If it can be done discreetly.

275
00:14:52,189 --> 00:14:54,234
Of course, you realize
this is strictly confidential?

276
00:14:54,618 --> 00:14:56,885
Mr Duryea, you can trust me implicitly.

277
00:14:57,674 --> 00:14:59,437
Now, what will it cost me?

278
00:14:59,804 --> 00:15:01,277
That will be two thousand a month.

279
00:15:01,600 --> 00:15:02,224
Hmm.

280
00:15:06,094 --> 00:15:09,479
Naturally, I don't want you
to steal any designs in Paris.

281
00:15:09,986 --> 00:15:11,109
But remember.

282
00:15:11,412 --> 00:15:14,637
Nobody must know about our arrangement.

283
00:15:15,245 --> 00:15:17,924
Señor Caponelli, you
can trust me implicitly.

284
00:15:18,215 --> 00:15:19,006
How much?

285
00:15:19,468 --> 00:15:20,999
That will be three thousand a month.

286
00:15:24,756 --> 00:15:26,426
Understand, Mr Nash.

287
00:15:27,072 --> 00:15:30,143
We don't want you to steal
models for us in Paris.

288
00:15:30,372 --> 00:15:31,720
No. That would be unethical.

289
00:15:32,305 --> 00:15:35,576
I'm telling you what has business
got to do with unethical?

290
00:15:35,676 --> 00:15:36,661
I tell you ..

291
00:15:36,761 --> 00:15:38,530
What you boys need is unique ..

292
00:15:38,883 --> 00:15:40,794
Personal representation in Paris. Right?

293
00:15:42,105 --> 00:15:43,682
That's exactly what I'll give you.

294
00:15:43,782 --> 00:15:45,667
You understand, Mr Nash.
This is confidential.

295
00:15:45,767 --> 00:15:48,831
Sure .. and besides,
not a word to nobody.

296
00:15:49,509 --> 00:15:51,370
Gentlemen, you can trust me implicitly.

297
00:15:51,693 --> 00:15:53,023
How much does it set us back?

298
00:15:53,134 --> 00:15:54,836
That will cost you five
thousand a month.

299
00:15:58,563 --> 00:16:00,981
Glad tidings my lad. Come and hear them.

300
00:16:01,168 --> 00:16:04,308
Well .. we were just about ready
to come down and bail you out.

301
00:16:04,517 --> 00:16:06,706
You won't have to do any bailing
unless we're shipwrecked.

302
00:16:07,054 --> 00:16:08,545
We sail for Paris tomorrow.

303
00:16:09,136 --> 00:16:10,466
Then it worked?
- It worked.

304
00:16:10,615 --> 00:16:12,221
Hey, ain't I in on this party?

305
00:16:13,052 --> 00:16:14,468
Now, what could you do in Paris?

306
00:16:16,261 --> 00:16:18,026
What wouldn't I do in Paris?

307
00:16:18,226 --> 00:16:20,558
We could take him along as chaperone.
You'll probably want one.

308
00:16:20,800 --> 00:16:23,080
Well, I don't want one,
but maybe I'll need one.

309
00:16:24,640 --> 00:16:27,169
Paris .. wine and women. Ha.

310
00:16:46,915 --> 00:16:47,530
Hey.

311
00:16:49,002 --> 00:16:50,103
There you are, Madam.

312
00:16:50,338 --> 00:16:50,953
Sir.

313
00:16:51,269 --> 00:16:52,056
Thank you.

314
00:16:57,352 --> 00:16:58,883
Well, believe it or not, we made it.

315
00:16:59,253 --> 00:17:01,327
I think I'll get on speaking
terms with my state room.

316
00:17:01,656 --> 00:17:03,979
I think I'll get on speaking
terms with the bar.

317
00:17:04,218 --> 00:17:06,121
Well I'll go and see you
don't talk it to death.

318
00:17:09,828 --> 00:17:10,815
Hello sweetheart.

319
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:13,576
You know darling, I think
I'm going to love Paris.

320
00:17:15,357 --> 00:17:16,580
Oh you do, huh?

321
00:17:18,618 --> 00:17:19,319
Glenda.

322
00:17:19,715 --> 00:17:23,151
Paris is one of the largest cities in
the world but too small to hold us both.

323
00:17:23,397 --> 00:17:26,679
You can go to Timbuktu for all
I care as long as I get my cut.

324
00:17:27,003 --> 00:17:27,618
Cut?

325
00:17:27,870 --> 00:17:28,909
What's the idea?

326
00:17:29,009 --> 00:17:31,687
Oh, just a little dash of that
efficiency you admired so much.

327
00:17:32,355 --> 00:17:33,399
Come on baby, give.

328
00:17:33,499 --> 00:17:35,164
Glenda, you know I don't owe you a cent.

329
00:17:35,264 --> 00:17:37,959
No argument. Either you
come across or I go across.

330
00:17:38,643 --> 00:17:40,115
[ Ship's horn. Loud ]

331
00:17:42,367 --> 00:17:43,125
How much?

332
00:17:43,606 --> 00:17:44,309
Oh.

333
00:17:45,167 --> 00:17:46,240
Three or four grand.

334
00:17:48,537 --> 00:17:49,480
Don't be silly.

335
00:17:51,125 --> 00:17:51,747
Oh.

336
00:17:52,288 --> 00:17:53,577
I beg your pardon.

337
00:17:56,358 --> 00:17:57,099
Glenda.

338
00:17:58,241 --> 00:18:00,071
I'll give you two grand
and that's the limit.

339
00:18:00,171 --> 00:18:01,679
Okay, big heart.

340
00:18:02,440 --> 00:18:03,624
Isn't this clubby.

341
00:18:03,833 --> 00:18:04,734
Yes, isn't it.

342
00:18:05,027 --> 00:18:07,234
Glenda came down to see me off.
- Isn't that lovely.

343
00:18:07,533 --> 00:18:08,973
The boat is sailing any minute.

344
00:18:09,073 --> 00:18:11,097
You'd better hurry ashore
unless you want to swim.

345
00:18:11,461 --> 00:18:13,176
A thousand thanks.
- Two thousand.

346
00:18:14,745 --> 00:18:15,672
Hurry, please.

347
00:18:16,426 --> 00:18:17,442
Hurry off, please.

348
00:18:17,601 --> 00:18:18,953
Just a moment, just a moment.

349
00:18:19,268 --> 00:18:20,257
Oh there she is.

350
00:18:20,357 --> 00:18:21,315
So long, Snappy.

351
00:18:21,912 --> 00:18:23,146
Get it?
- You bet I did.

352
00:18:23,246 --> 00:18:25,104
So long, Snappy.
- Hope you land a nice job.

353
00:18:25,204 --> 00:18:28,165
Don't worry. Harry and I go in business
where you and the mastermind left off.

354
00:18:28,466 --> 00:18:30,997
Hey .. good luck to you, darling.

355
00:18:31,172 --> 00:18:33,188
No hard feelings.
Come on, give us a little kiss.

356
00:18:33,288 --> 00:18:35,423
Sorry, but you must leave.
- Oh, I must say goodbye.

357
00:18:35,523 --> 00:18:36,440
I'm sorry.

358
00:18:36,669 --> 00:18:37,627
So long, Glenda.

359
00:18:38,162 --> 00:18:39,437
What did you get?
- Guess.

360
00:18:39,537 --> 00:18:40,525
A grand?
- Two.

361
00:18:40,761 --> 00:18:41,784
What a woman.

362
00:18:42,602 --> 00:18:43,389
It's gone.

363
00:18:43,650 --> 00:18:44,661
Ha-ha-ha.

364
00:18:45,881 --> 00:18:47,365
Ha-ha-ha.

365
00:18:59,560 --> 00:19:02,054
Boy, have I got something to show you.

366
00:19:02,271 --> 00:19:02,985
Yes?

367
00:19:04,126 --> 00:19:06,124
Holy smoke. I've been robbed.

368
00:19:06,600 --> 00:19:07,933
No.
- Yes.

369
00:19:08,597 --> 00:19:10,271
How much was it?
- Two thousand dollars.

370
00:19:10,711 --> 00:19:11,593
Two thousand?

371
00:19:12,386 --> 00:19:13,316
That's right.

372
00:20:37,301 --> 00:20:38,704
Do you like any of them, dear?

373
00:20:38,804 --> 00:20:41,164
They are very nice but they're
not exactly what I'm looking for.

374
00:20:41,671 --> 00:20:43,516
Haven't you something
a little more exclusive?

375
00:20:43,616 --> 00:20:45,347
These are our latest creations, Madame.

376
00:20:45,447 --> 00:20:48,521
Oh come now, Madame.
Haven't you something really new?

377
00:20:49,009 --> 00:20:50,472
Something that hasn't been shown?

378
00:20:51,273 --> 00:20:52,143
I will see.

379
00:20:52,475 --> 00:20:54,277
Wait, Monsieur.
- Merci, Madame.

380
00:21:04,383 --> 00:21:06,200
Better keep working
on the old girl in black.

381
00:21:06,852 --> 00:21:08,265
She's a pretty tough bird.

382
00:21:08,912 --> 00:21:10,242
Turn on your charm, Sherwood.

383
00:21:10,581 --> 00:21:11,975
No woman can resist you.

384
00:21:13,773 --> 00:21:15,332
Your resistance is still pretty good.

385
00:21:21,736 --> 00:21:22,866
Just a minute, please.

386
00:21:23,186 --> 00:21:24,397
Just a moment, please.

387
00:21:27,936 --> 00:21:29,315
I'd like to see that again.

388
00:21:29,673 --> 00:21:30,690
Once more?

389
00:21:42,639 --> 00:21:44,896
What time do you relaxez-vous?

390
00:21:48,097 --> 00:21:48,884
Hey, Snap.

391
00:21:51,186 --> 00:21:52,373
You are right, governor.

392
00:22:07,998 --> 00:22:10,956
This is very special, Monsieur.
It has not yet been shown to the trade.

393
00:22:13,449 --> 00:22:14,236
Very nice.

394
00:22:14,681 --> 00:22:15,345
Hmm.

395
00:22:15,965 --> 00:22:17,943
I'm afraid it is rather extreme for me.

396
00:22:18,258 --> 00:22:21,262
Well you don't have to decide now, dear.
Why don't you think it over?

397
00:22:21,646 --> 00:22:22,576
I think I will.

398
00:22:23,050 --> 00:22:23,751
Oh yes.

399
00:22:24,244 --> 00:22:26,776
You've been more than obliging, Madame.
- It was a pleasure, Monsieur.

400
00:22:27,053 --> 00:22:28,898
I hope we haven't put you
to too much trouble.

401
00:22:29,062 --> 00:22:30,643
Au revoir.

402
00:23:04,065 --> 00:23:06,692
What I could do to a
nice juicy hamburger.

403
00:23:07,171 --> 00:23:09,051
One can think better
on an empty stomach.

404
00:23:09,314 --> 00:23:12,229
Yeah? I ought to be able to do
some elegant thinking right now.

405
00:23:12,437 --> 00:23:13,949
Filthy pictures?
- What?

406
00:23:14,179 --> 00:23:15,137
Filthy pictures.

407
00:23:18,489 --> 00:23:20,193
Merci, Monsieur Baroque.

408
00:23:20,491 --> 00:23:21,762
Au revoir, mon ami.

409
00:23:24,240 --> 00:23:25,026
Au revoir.

410
00:23:34,867 --> 00:23:37,275
Pardon Monsieur. Parlez-vous anglais?

411
00:23:37,718 --> 00:23:39,209
Sure.
- Oh, swell.

412
00:23:39,485 --> 00:23:40,100
Say.

413
00:23:40,403 --> 00:23:42,095
Was that Baroque, the couturier?

414
00:23:43,249 --> 00:23:45,598
Sure. There is only one Baroque.

415
00:23:46,503 --> 00:23:48,381
Is he a customer of yours?
- Yes.

416
00:23:48,643 --> 00:23:51,445
He buys all these ancient
books on costumes from me.

417
00:23:52,016 --> 00:23:53,230
Sherry.
- Huh?

418
00:23:54,629 --> 00:23:56,016
Does that look familiar to you?

419
00:23:57,245 --> 00:23:58,032
Why, sure.

420
00:23:58,323 --> 00:24:00,771
It's exactly like one of those
models we saw at Baroques.

421
00:24:00,991 --> 00:24:02,119
You see, Monsieur.

422
00:24:02,433 --> 00:24:05,002
The fashion is like .. how you say it?

423
00:24:05,310 --> 00:24:06,039
A cycle.

424
00:24:06,267 --> 00:24:10,236
What is passé now will be the
fashion in maybe fifty years.

425
00:24:10,621 --> 00:24:11,723
Maybe a hundred.

426
00:24:12,071 --> 00:24:14,126
Baroque gets all his ideas
from books like these.

427
00:24:31,894 --> 00:24:34,229
Say, I'll take this. How much is it?

428
00:24:35,047 --> 00:24:36,120
Seventy-five Francs.

429
00:24:38,930 --> 00:24:39,717
Hey, Snap.

430
00:24:40,293 --> 00:24:41,709
Would you let me have 25 Francs?

431
00:24:42,386 --> 00:24:43,356
I'm flat.

432
00:24:45,941 --> 00:24:47,574
Thank you.
- I had just 25 left.

433
00:24:48,176 --> 00:24:49,744
Au Revoir, Monsieur.
- Au Revoir.

434
00:24:51,675 --> 00:24:55,128
Hey, we're starving to death and
you buy old books. What's the idea?

435
00:24:56,268 --> 00:24:57,312
I've been thinking.

436
00:24:57,779 --> 00:25:00,339
See here. If Baroque can borrow
from the past, why can't you?

437
00:25:00,615 --> 00:25:01,651
I can easily.

438
00:25:02,225 --> 00:25:03,643
Who wants to buy my sketches?

439
00:25:03,884 --> 00:25:06,583
Ah, but when they reach our New York
clients they won't be <i>your</i> sketches.

440
00:25:06,983 --> 00:25:09,006
A little gentle forgery
will take care of that.

441
00:25:09,495 --> 00:25:11,939
They will then bear the distinguishes
signatures of Baroque ..

442
00:25:12,466 --> 00:25:13,640
Savarin and DeVrille.

443
00:25:14,185 --> 00:25:15,918
Do I make myself clear, Lieutenant?

444
00:25:16,524 --> 00:25:17,841
Very clear, Captain.

445
00:25:33,880 --> 00:25:34,974
Why, Tibby.

446
00:25:35,949 --> 00:25:37,908
You ought to be ashamed of yourself.

447
00:25:45,447 --> 00:25:47,548
You may wait, Perkins.
- Shut up, sir.

448
00:25:48,207 --> 00:25:49,743
Is something troubling you, my man?

449
00:25:49,843 --> 00:25:51,802
I'm tired of being dressed
up in this monkey suit.

450
00:25:52,223 --> 00:25:54,030
Don't crab Perkins,
we must keep up a punt.

451
00:25:54,284 --> 00:25:55,553
Besides, I'm hungry.

452
00:25:56,672 --> 00:25:57,908
Don't be crude, Perkins.

453
00:26:01,189 --> 00:26:02,876
Bonjour Monsieur.

454
00:26:03,339 --> 00:26:04,126
Hiya, Kid.

455
00:26:07,748 --> 00:26:09,787
Hey, come here with that key.
What's the idea?

456
00:26:10,992 --> 00:26:12,048
Ah, good morning.

457
00:26:12,925 --> 00:26:13,797
Good morning.

458
00:26:14,457 --> 00:26:16,901
My dear, I only stopped in at
the Ritz bar for a few minutes.

459
00:26:17,447 --> 00:26:18,675
What pried you loose?

460
00:26:19,231 --> 00:26:23,042
Do I detect a slight note, a
mere soupçon of disapproval?

461
00:26:23,792 --> 00:26:25,120
Listen Sherry, I'm worried.

462
00:26:25,635 --> 00:26:28,533
Ah. No news from New York, huh?
- No. Not a nickel's worth.

463
00:26:29,859 --> 00:26:31,533
Say, that's pretty good.

464
00:26:32,424 --> 00:26:34,375
Pretty good? I'll have
you know it's very good.

465
00:26:34,763 --> 00:26:36,621
What is it? Savarin or DeVrille?

466
00:26:36,884 --> 00:26:39,753
No, stupid. 24 carat pure Baroque.

467
00:26:41,390 --> 00:26:42,223
Of course.

468
00:26:44,319 --> 00:26:45,077
Now look.

469
00:26:50,215 --> 00:26:51,545
Signed by the master himself.

470
00:26:52,020 --> 00:26:54,096
Here is a perfect Savarin.

471
00:26:55,387 --> 00:26:56,236
Savarin.

472
00:26:58,322 --> 00:26:58,994
Voila.

473
00:27:00,266 --> 00:27:00,995
Come in.

474
00:27:02,374 --> 00:27:03,964
Bonjour Monsieur Nash.
- Bonjour.

475
00:27:04,510 --> 00:27:05,182
Merci.

476
00:27:05,539 --> 00:27:06,254
Duryea.

477
00:27:08,088 --> 00:27:08,984
Let us pray.

478
00:27:13,216 --> 00:27:15,834
He is glad to see that our cable
complaining of delay resulted in action.

479
00:27:16,270 --> 00:27:18,487
He congratulates you on obtaining
these excellent sketches.

480
00:27:18,633 --> 00:27:20,882
And predicts the models will
be large sellers in New York.

481
00:27:21,188 --> 00:27:22,787
Enclosed, please find our check ..

482
00:27:24,158 --> 00:27:24,830
For ..

483
00:27:25,802 --> 00:27:27,398
Five hundred dollars.

484
00:27:27,864 --> 00:27:29,151
Oh baby, we've made it.

485
00:27:36,663 --> 00:27:38,278
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

486
00:27:38,855 --> 00:27:41,342
I'm not accustomed to having
people holler at me like this.

487
00:27:41,632 --> 00:27:43,538
Besides, I don't know
what you're talking about.

488
00:27:43,930 --> 00:27:45,047
Beat it. Beat it.

489
00:27:49,302 --> 00:27:50,840
Nuts .. nuts .. nuts.

490
00:27:51,328 --> 00:27:51,971
Nuts.

491
00:27:52,427 --> 00:27:54,443
Noisettes. Noisettes.

492
00:27:54,799 --> 00:27:56,980
I demand the courtesy due a foreigner.

493
00:28:02,381 --> 00:28:03,917
Well, what seems to be the trouble?

494
00:28:04,017 --> 00:28:06,606
I don't know. This guy grabs the key
and then they both start hollering.

495
00:28:14,381 --> 00:28:15,196
What is it?

496
00:28:15,635 --> 00:28:17,975
Payment on the car. Slightly overdue.

497
00:28:18,397 --> 00:28:19,289
How much?

498
00:28:20,657 --> 00:28:21,758
Five hundred dollars.

499
00:28:23,275 --> 00:28:25,031
Oh well .. that's a cinch.

500
00:28:26,155 --> 00:28:28,683
Avez-vous la plume de ma mere?

501
00:28:32,076 --> 00:28:33,885
I'll .. just endorse this.

502
00:28:36,931 --> 00:28:37,603
Voila.

503
00:28:37,703 --> 00:28:38,718
La clef, Monsieur.

504
00:28:39,255 --> 00:28:39,927
Merci.

505
00:28:41,805 --> 00:28:42,999
Au revoir. Au revoir.

506
00:28:43,602 --> 00:28:45,530
What's it all about?
Are we in the money again?

507
00:28:45,630 --> 00:28:46,917
We were, for a minute.

508
00:28:47,215 --> 00:28:48,717
Yes. Now you see it, and now don't.

509
00:28:49,060 --> 00:28:51,318
What do you mean?
- It's a long story, Perkins.

510
00:28:51,775 --> 00:28:54,036
The Embassy.
- What are we going to use for money?

511
00:28:54,573 --> 00:28:56,132
Don't worry. I'll think of something.

512
00:29:08,604 --> 00:29:09,784
And for you, Monsieur?

513
00:29:10,242 --> 00:29:12,431
Champagne cocktails.
- Champagne cocktails. Oui, Monsieur.

514
00:29:12,814 --> 00:29:13,715
Are you crazy?

515
00:29:14,207 --> 00:29:15,537
Who is going to pay for them?

516
00:29:15,989 --> 00:29:18,159
My dear, they say if you stay
at this bar long enough ..

517
00:29:18,259 --> 00:29:19,789
You'll meet everybody in the world.

518
00:29:20,169 --> 00:29:22,452
Do you think I might meet
somebody with a sandwich?

519
00:29:23,225 --> 00:29:26,777
Now don't be a pessimist, my dear.
Why, the world is our oyster.

520
00:29:27,009 --> 00:29:28,784
What did you say? What did you say?

521
00:29:29,119 --> 00:29:31,006
I say the world is our oyster.

522
00:29:31,641 --> 00:29:33,241
Oh, oysters ain't in season.

523
00:29:33,768 --> 00:29:35,518
Ah, now don't you be a pessimist.

524
00:29:38,620 --> 00:29:39,966
Cheerio, Mr Ward.

525
00:29:40,776 --> 00:29:41,992
How did you know my name?

526
00:29:42,767 --> 00:29:45,232
Well my dear sir, I happen to
have the gift of second sight.

527
00:29:47,100 --> 00:29:49,279
And you seem to be depressed.
Is something on your mind?

528
00:29:49,980 --> 00:29:51,835
I say, my name is Sherwood Nash.

529
00:29:52,086 --> 00:29:53,739
Hello.
- Maybe I can help you?

530
00:29:54,098 --> 00:29:56,319
Yes. It would be much better
if your name was Houdini.

531
00:29:56,692 --> 00:29:58,223
Hold on, look at this. Look at this.

532
00:30:01,378 --> 00:30:02,680
How about a little sandwich?

533
00:30:05,937 --> 00:30:07,531
Here, look at that. Look at that.

534
00:30:08,363 --> 00:30:09,367
A lovely plume.

535
00:30:09,467 --> 00:30:11,259
I can sell you 10,000 gross of those.

536
00:30:11,565 --> 00:30:13,703
Quality A number one.
Immediate delivery.

537
00:30:14,043 --> 00:30:15,552
And ten percent discount for cash.

538
00:30:15,652 --> 00:30:17,371
Sorry old man, but
I'm not in the market.

539
00:30:17,471 --> 00:30:19,691
No. I know, nobody is. Nobody is.

540
00:30:19,904 --> 00:30:22,595
No. I got a thousand
ostriches out in California.

541
00:30:22,800 --> 00:30:25,501
Eating their heads off but I
haven't sold a feather in a year.

542
00:30:27,238 --> 00:30:28,114
Why is that?

543
00:30:28,214 --> 00:30:30,741
I don't know. Ostrich feathers
ain't like cheese and flour.

544
00:30:31,004 --> 00:30:32,248
They are always in demand.

545
00:30:32,912 --> 00:30:35,213
But plumes like mine? No. I give up.

546
00:30:36,611 --> 00:30:37,493
Well.

547
00:30:47,122 --> 00:30:49,045
[ French language ]

548
00:30:55,220 --> 00:30:56,836
Garçon.
- Oui, Monsieur?

549
00:30:58,368 --> 00:30:59,956
Who is the lady with Monsieur Baroque?

550
00:31:01,700 --> 00:31:04,170
Grand Duchess Alex.
Refugee from Imperial Russia.

551
00:31:05,946 --> 00:31:06,663
Merci.

552
00:31:13,518 --> 00:31:15,795
Mr Ward .. I think I think
you've come to the right man.

553
00:31:15,895 --> 00:31:16,573
Yes?

554
00:31:16,766 --> 00:31:18,591
In fact, I'm going to congratulate you.

555
00:31:18,940 --> 00:31:19,727
On what?

556
00:31:20,431 --> 00:31:21,943
You have some capital, haven't you?

557
00:31:22,043 --> 00:31:23,288
Oh, have I.

558
00:31:23,388 --> 00:31:25,200
And you have thousands
of ostrich feathers?

559
00:31:25,300 --> 00:31:26,590
Oh, you are telling me?

560
00:31:27,228 --> 00:31:29,989
How would you like me to put
ostrich feathers across for you?

561
00:31:30,188 --> 00:31:30,866
Fine.

562
00:31:30,966 --> 00:31:33,934
How would you like me to make the world
of fashion so feather-conscious ..

563
00:31:34,218 --> 00:31:35,937
That every well-dressed
woman in Paris ..

564
00:31:36,037 --> 00:31:38,648
Will be dripping, floating,
foaming with ostrich feathers?

565
00:31:38,889 --> 00:31:42,004
If you can do that Mr Nash, it would
be worth fifty thousand dollars to you.

566
00:31:42,247 --> 00:31:44,190
Will you give me that in writing?
- Absolutely.

567
00:31:44,643 --> 00:31:46,030
But how are you going to do it?

568
00:31:46,130 --> 00:31:48,154
I just said I had second sight, right?
- Yes.

569
00:31:48,431 --> 00:31:49,535
Leave it all to me.

570
00:31:56,322 --> 00:31:57,166
What's this?

571
00:31:57,889 --> 00:32:00,713
Oh well thank you very much,
Mr Ward. That's very generous of you.

572
00:32:01,287 --> 00:32:03,863
But I insist that the next time,
I be permitted to buy the drinks.

573
00:32:04,087 --> 00:32:04,894
Oh yes.

574
00:32:15,168 --> 00:32:16,727
But I don't know this man. Who is he?

575
00:32:16,998 --> 00:32:20,043
